# Skippy browser extension

## Layout

- `plugin/` is the single loadable extension root for **Firefox and Chrome** â€” no per-browser forks.
- `ext.js` is the only place for `browser` / `chrome` branching; other files call `getStorage()`.
- Do not add build tooling or repo docs inside `plugin/` unless the extension needs them at runtime.

## Cross-browser APIs

```javascript
// ext.js â€” do not duplicate this pattern elsewhere
const ext = typeof globalThis.browser !== "undefined" ? globalThis.browser : globalThis.chrome;
```

Load `ext.js` before `processor.js` (manifest `content_scripts`) and before `popup.js` (popup.html).

## Manifest (MV3)

- `manifest_version: 3`; toolbar UI uses `action`, not `browser_action`.
- API fetch permission lives in `host_permissions`; `storage` stays in `permissions`.
- Bump `version` for any user-facing release.
- `browser_specific_settings.gecko` is Firefox-only (add-on ID); Chrome ignores it.
- No background service worker unless new features require one.
- Content scripts only run on `https://www.youtube.com/watch*` â€” broaden matches deliberately.

## Content script (`processor.js`)

- Polls storage for the server base URL; appends `/api/v2/timestamps` â€” never hardcode full API URLs in popup placeholder text.
- Detects SPA navigation via History API hooks + URL polling â€” preserve this when refactoring video-change detection.
- Skip check uses throttled `timeupdate` on the active `<video>` (250ms); clear listeners in `stopTracking()` before re-attaching on video change.
- API returns `{ status: "pending" }` (HTTP 202) or `{ status: "ready", intervals: [...] }` (HTTP 200); poll every 3s while pending.
- Validate ready responses with `parseIntervals()`; cancel polls and ignore stale fetches via `fetchGeneration` + `video_ref`.

## Popup (`popup.js` / `popup.html`)

- Server URL is the **base origin** only (e.g. `https://api.example.com`), saved to `storage.sync` under key `server`.
- Register event listeners once (inside `DOMContentLoaded`).

## Testing checklist

1. Reload unpacked extension in **Firefox and Chrome** after any `plugin/` change.
2. Refresh open YouTube tabs (content scripts do not hot-reload).
3. Set server URL in popup â†’ confirm `storage.sync` persists across browser restart.
4. Open a watch URL â†’ verify GET to `/api/v2/timestamps?link=...` in Network tab.
5. With known timestamps, confirm playback jumps past `start_time`â€“`end_time` ranges.
6. Navigate to another video without full page reload â†’ confirm new timestamps are fetched.

## Scope discipline

- Minimal diffs; no frameworks or bundlers unless the project outgrows vanilla JS.
- Keep console prefix `[YouTube Tracker]` consistent unless renaming project-wide.
